<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,310,448,474]" box="[189,310,448,474]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,448,474]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,448,474]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,1399,496,669]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Similar to 
<emphasis box="[313,538,496,523]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Eckstein" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[313,535,496,523]" class="Insecta" family="Adelgidae" genus="Adelges" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nordmannianae">
A. 
<taxonomicName box="[346,535,496,522]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="nordmannianae">nordmannianae</taxonomicName>
</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Neosistens: wax pore plates on inner margins of meso- and metathoracic spinal sclerites divided into 3–4 rounded areas, each with 3–8 pits. Total number of pits on the 10 central areas 26–63 (usually more than 40) (
<bibRefCitation author="Blackman R. L. &amp; Eastop V. F." box="[700,1000,569,596]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refId="ref17823" refString="Blackman R. L. &amp; Eastop V. F. 1994. Aphids on the World's Trees. CAB International, Wallingford." type="book" year="1994">Blackman &amp; Eastop 1994</bibRefCitation>
, 2014). Holocyclic and dioecious, alternating between 
<taxonomicName box="[426,612,606,632]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Picea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis box="[426,612,606,632]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName box="[426,493,607,632]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Picea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Picea</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[500,612,606,632]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="orientalis">orientalis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(p. 9) and 
<taxonomicName box="[738,862,606,632]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Abies" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis box="[738,862,606,632]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName box="[738,803,606,632]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Abies" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Abies</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[810,862,606,632]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="alba">alba</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Scattered on trunk and older branches, on all parts of seedlings. Not ant-attended.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
